column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

Numbers eased with rain predicted in the supply area. The quality was a bit plainer on the lighter cattle but there were good lines and medium and heavy feeder steers and heifers. Trade cattle were not as well supplied but some feeder orders were buying cattle with more condition. Prime grown cattle were in reduced numbers and there were more heavy export weight feeders. The cow run was plainer and much smaller, heavy 3 and 4 score cows were limited. The market sold to stronger trends.
 
Light calves reached 470c to restocking orders and 490c/kg for the vealers. Feeder steers were 15c to 20c stronger and for the second week running crossbreds were the stronger selling. Medium weights sold from 355c to 398c and heavy weights 311c to 390c/kg. Feeder heifers were 15c dearer with most ranging from 282c to 335c/kg. The trade cattle were 8c to 12c dearer with the best steers reaching 377c and heifers 334c/kg.
 
Heavy export feeders jumped 12c and reached 368c/kg. Prime grown steers and bullocks were 2c to 8c stronger selling between 320c and 340c and the prime heavy grown heifers lifted 12c to 18c with the bulk ranging from 310c to 340c/kg. The heavy cows were 3c to 4c dearer selling from 258c to 289c but the plainer medium weight 2 scores were 11c cheaper selling from 230c to 259c/kg.
